Provision the Infrastructure :
Open your terminal and create your project folder: 
mkdir ~/docker-swarm-vms && cd ~/docker-swarm-vms
Create the Vagrantfile using the 3-node configuration provided earlier.
Run vagrant up to boot manager-vm, worker1-vm, and worker2-vm.

Configure the Docker Swarm Cluster :
SSH into the manager: vagrant ssh manager-vm.
Install Docker: sudo apt update && sudo apt install -y docker.io 
(add the vagrant user to the docker group).
Initialize the Swarm: docker swarm init --advertise-addr 192.168.56.10.
Copy the generated docker swarm join --token... command.
SSH into worker1-vm and worker2-vm, install Docker, and paste the join command in each.

Develop the Simple Java Application :
Create a new directory for your app: mkdir ~/simple-java-app && cd ~/simple-java-app.
Create the src/main/java/com/example/App.java file (using the simple ServerSocket on port 9090).
Create the simplified pom.xml to build the JAR.
Create the Dockerfile that builds the Maven project and exposes port 9090.
Create the Jenkinsfile (ensuring you update IMAGE_NAME with your Docker Hub username).

Push Code to GitHub : 
Initialize Git in your simple-java-app folder: git init.
Add and commit all files: git add . && git commit -m "Initial commit".
Link it to your GitHub repository and push: git remote add origin <URL> then git push -u origin main.

Prepare Jenkins and Docker Hub : 
Generate a Docker Hub Access Token from your Docker Hub account settings.
On the manager VM, start Jenkins:
docker run -p 8080:8080 -p 50000:50000 -d -v jenkins_home:/var/jenkins_home -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock --name jenkins jenkins/jenkins:lts

Fix Jenkins permissions so it can build images: run sudo chmod 666 /var/run/docker.sock on the manager VM, then install the Docker CLI inside the Jenkins container as root.
Access Jenkins at [http://192.168.56.10:8080](http://192.168.56.10:8080), complete the initial setup, and add your Docker Hub token under Manage Jenkins > Credentials with the ID dockerhub-creds.

Deploy the Initial Swarm Service : 
Before Jenkins can update a service, the service must exist. Run this once on the manager VM to create the baseline application:
docker service create --name java-web-app --replicas 3 -p 9090:9090 yourdockerhubuser/simple-java-app:latest


Configure the Automated Pipeline : 

In Jenkins, click New Item, name it, and select Pipeline.
Under Build Triggers, check Build periodically and enter H/15 * * * * (this tells Jenkins to check GitHub every 15 minutes).
Under Pipeline, select Pipeline script from SCM, choose Git, and paste your GitHub repository URL.
Save and click Build Now to run the first test manually.
